Located in the extension of the Richard Lenoir promenade of the same name, this tree-lined square is well laid out. This square is one of the four gardens that make up the Richard-Lenoir promenade, built on a vault since Haussmann, whose recent developments have been designed to recall the existence of the Saint-Martin canal under the cobblestones. The square pays homage to the fabric manufacturers Fran√ßois Richard (1765-1839) and Joseph Lenoir-Dufresne (4768-1806), who created the first cotton factory in 1802. Fran√ßois Richard changed his name to Fran√ßois Richard-Lenoir upon the death of the second.
